<font color="#FF0000">TO SILENT WARRIOR &amp; COOK</font><br>
<tt>Fri Sep 12  0:33:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
SW - words worthy of learning, I thank you for them. I see the pack mentality rear it ugly hear within this site, and I scream.  You offer reason to my troubled soul, and I thank you for that. Your post is truly a salve to my troubled soul.  <br><br>
I want not revenge, nor equality. I could never hope to be equal to the savagery of the jungle and the firefight, nor do I want to. I could never be equal to the boot camp experience, nor do I seek it. I want not to be a murderer although murder is certainly in my heart.  Had you met me in the jungle, I certainly would have pulled the trigger. <br><br>
I took the road that I did, because it was in my heart. When someone like Richard posts, a resistor who ran to Canada, I am troubled, but I accept him. I choose a different fight.  The point is, behind all of our bullshit, is that we all had the ability to choose......to accept the draft boards verdict and go...to follow the letter from the selective service and go....or the appointment letter with the induction center, and go.....or to say, NO, this is wrong, I won't do it.  <br><br>
That critical decision hit us all at different times, and in different ways.  Some ran, Some enlisted, some got drafted, some got escaped.  <br><br>
Now 30+ years later, we try and make sense of it all.  Can we? God, the jungle experience looks so exciting, so rambo, now, to me. 30 years ago it scared the hell out of me. It also was wrong, but that was second to my fear.  My fear was politically correct, however, and your rambo-ism was not, later in history. My fear was just to stay alive.<br><br>
Where are we now, all of us are brothers of Vietnam, be it in the jungle, or at the draft board, at the border of Laos, or Canada, our generation was shaped by this madness.  If we can not agree to this simple agreement, then we truly are lost.  The war was lost, our generation was lost, but do we still need to throw stones at each other, as Cook and I are doing, when we should be embraced in a hug, saying &quot;those MotherF.....er's, they will never get my kids, like they tricked me.&quot;.  Hey Cook, can you hear me calling?
<p><code>-- posted  (Doc Spatz) </code><p>


